  "slug": "cupcakes-lemon",
  "title": "Lemon cupcakes",
  "subtitle": "Zesty lemon sponge with lemon buttercream",
  "excerpt": "A light lemon sponge with zest worked into the batter, topped with a sharp lemon buttercream. More lemony than a Victoria sponge; a little less sweet than the American original.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "The lemon cupcake is a standard of American bakeries adapted for British tastes, which typically prefer less sweetness in the frosting and a stronger citrus note in the sponge. This recipe synthesises the British Victoria sponge proportions with the American cupcake format, adjusting sugar downward in the buttercream relative to the Hummingbird Bakery original (Tim Malouf, 2009).",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The lemon flavour in these cupcakes comes from two places: zest rubbed into the sugar (which extracts the fragrant oils) and lemon juice in the buttercream. Both matter. Zest alone gives aroma but little sharpness; juice alone gives acid but can turn the buttercream grainy. Together they give the full lemon profile.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "infoPanel",
        "attrs": {
          "type": "tip"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "text": "Use unwaxed lemons. Waxed lemon zest contains a bitter resin coating that comes through in the baked sponge. If you can only find waxed lemons, scrub them vigorously in hot water and dry before zesting.",
                "type": "text"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
